TY  - JOUR
T1  - Age Stereotypes as a Function Of Race
AU  - Crew, James C.
Y1  - 1984/06/01
PY  - 1984
DA  - 1984/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255934
DO  - 10.5465/255934
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 431
EP  - 435
VL  - 27
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article discusses research pertaining to the effect of race on age stereotyped attitudes. Black and white business students were asked to rate 30-year old and 60-year old workers based on work-related dimensions including performance capacity, potential for development, stability, and interpersonal skills. In the study black students always rated older workers lower than younger workers. The results indicate that black respondents held more extreme age stereotypes than their white counterparts. Experts speculate that the differences may be due to scholastic achievement factors.
AB  - The article discusses research pertaining to the effect of race on age stereotyped attitudes. Black and white business students were asked to rate 30-year old and 60-year old workers based on work-related dimensions including performance capacity, potential for development, stability, and interpersonal skills. In the study black students always rated older workers lower than younger workers. The results indicate that black respondents held more extreme age stereotypes than their white counterparts. Experts speculate that the differences may be due to scholastic achievement factors.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/255934
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/255934
Y2  - 2026/04/24
